# Axis 22 — fresh nested prompt isolation

Two distinct effects are two distinct prompts. A `shift` on prompt `p` is NOT captured
by a nested reset for a different prompt `q`: `q`'s handler does not match it and
forwards it (residual forwarding) out to `p`'s reset. Because `p`'s shift discards its
continuation — the `+ 1000` and the `q` boundary alike — the answer is just 7, proving
the two prompts are isolated.

```scalascript
effect CtlP:
  def shift(): Int
effect CtlQ:
  def use(): Int

def prog(): Int = handle {
  val throughQ = handle {
    CtlP.shift()
  } {
    case CtlQ.use(resume) => 999
  }
  throughQ + 1000
} {
  case CtlP.shift(resume) => 7
}

println(prog())
```
